</table>
<p>Act 2 begins with a short Prelude, based on a melody that José will sing offstage before his next entry.<sup id="cite_ref-D221_31-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-D221-31"><span>[</span>29<span>]</span></a></sup> A festive scene in the inn precedes Escamillo's tumultuous entrance and <a href="Toreador_Song" title="Toreador Song">his famous song</a>, in which <a href="Brass_instrument" title="Brass instrument">brass</a> and <a href="Percussion" title="Percussion" class="mw-redirect">percussion</a> provide prominent backing while the crowd sings along.<sup id="cite_ref-A16_70-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-A16-70"><span>[</span>67<span>]</span></a></sup> The quintet that follows is described by Newman as "of incomparable verve and musical wit".<sup id="cite_ref-87" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-87"><span>[</span>82<span>]</span></a></sup> José's appearance precipitates a long mutual wooing scene; Carmen sings, dances and plays the <a href="Castanets" title="Castanets">castanets</a>; a distant cornet-call summoning José to duty is blended with Carmen's melody so as to be barely discernible.<sup id="cite_ref-88" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-88"><span>[</span>83<span>]</span></a></sup> A muted reference to the fate motif on an <a href="Cor_anglais" title="Cor anglais">English horn</a> leads to José's "Flower Song", a flowing continuous melody that ends <i>pianissimo</i> on a sustained high <a href="B%E2%99%AD_(musical_note)" title="B♭ (musical note)">B-flat</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-89" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-89"><span>[</span>84<span>]</span></a></sup> José's insistence that, despite Carmen's blandishments, he must return to duty leads to a quarrel; the arrival of Zuniga, the consequent fight and José's unavoidable ensnarement into the lawless life culminates musically in the triumphant hymn to freedom that closes the act.<sup id="cite_ref-A16_70-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-A16-70"><span>[</span>67<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
